#4568
@@gRoot-Weave Quarter Entry@@N~
@@gThe root-weave houses begin here â structures built into the buttress
roots of the ancient flood-plain trees, their walls woven from split root
cuttings and the gaps chinked with clay mixed with ash. @@gThe technique
is genuinely old: the founding generation developed it as a way of building
without fighting the root systems that the Paradise Thesis described as
partners.@@N @@gThe result is architecture that feels grown rather than
built, the walls curving with the root profiles and the rooflines following
canopy angles. @@gSome houses have clearly been rebuilt since the original
construction, their replacement sections slightly more angular and slightly
less integrated.@@N @@WA Promise Stone is set into the root mass of the
largest tree at the quarter's entry; this one has no crack and its pledge
text â concerning civic enoughness â is still fully legible.@@N
